{"id":409,"date":"2008-08-31T10:57:51","date_gmt":"2008-08-31T18:57:51","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wordpress\/?p=409"},"modified":"2008-08-31T10:57:51","modified_gmt":"2008-08-31T18:57:51","slug":"love-and-authentication","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/2008\/08\/love-and-authentication\/","title":{"rendered":"love and authentication"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>Being able to say whether you like whale watching, country music and going to bookstores is a more secure way to verify your identity than your mother&#8217;s maiden name according to the SigCHI 2008 paper, <a href=\"http:\/\/portal.acm.org\/citation.cfm?id=1357054.1357087&amp;coll=ACM&amp;dl=ACM&amp;type=series&amp;idx=SERIES260&amp;part=series&amp;WantType=Proceedings&amp;title=CHI&amp;CFID=1106749&amp;CFTOKEN=50335438\">Love and authentication<\/a>.  A lot of the so-called security questions ask for information that is a matter of public record, such as your mother&#8217;s maiden name or your city of birth.  Markus Jakobsson, Erik Stolterman, Susanne Wetzel, and Liu Yang have looked at the kinds of questions you might answer for a match-making site which, as a collection, are unique to you and are quite hard to guess, even for folks who know you well.  &#8220;When subsets with at least 16 questions are used, the resulting error rates are tolerable, and for subsets of size 24 or greater they are very low.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p>I think it would be awkward to ask someone to fill out such a long form when they register for a site, but it would be intriguing if it could be somehow connected to the purpose of the site.  For some applications, this could make registration more fun and more secure.<\/p>\n<p>More info at <a href=\"http:\/\/www.i-forgot-my-password.com\">www.i-forgot-my-password.com<\/a>.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Being able to say whether you like whale watching, country music and going to bookstores is a more secu